A 32-year-old bank manager in the German&nbsp;city of Hanover admitted to a court on Tuesday that he organized a heist last year at the local branch of Santander that he ran.A court spokesperson said an accomplice who&nbsp;worked at the bank also admitted to the robbery of 467,500 euros ($510,000) last June.On the instructions of the bank manager, the accomplice threatened a third bank employee not involved in the robbery with a gun and forced him to open a safe. The bank manager looked on and pretended to be a victim.The two men then used the stolen money to buy sports cars and planned to buy apartments and expensive wristwatches, a court spokesperson said. Send Facebook Twitter Google+ Whatsapp Tumblr linkedin stumble Digg reddit Newsvine Permalink http://p.dw.com/p/2aul9cw/jm&nbsp;(dpa, HAZ)